{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"962"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/962"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.22,0.14,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"962"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/962"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"962"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90596"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"284"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing breathlessness during moderate activity such as walking with his wife and doing labour around the house. He reports occasional central chest pain during walks which resolves after rest. He has a medical history of osteoarthritis. He takes paracetamol sustained-release as needed. He has a 20-pack year smoking history and drinks two to three standard drinks of alcohol per day. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His baseline ECG shows no abnormalities. His GP refers him for an exercise stress test for further evaluation. His stress test at four minutes is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Angiography","Transoesophageal echocardiography","Continuing the stress test","Coronary artery bypass grafting","Thrombolysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man has multiple cardiovascular risk factors including a history of smoking and alcohol consumption. Further to this he is symptomatic of cardiovascular compromise as demonstrated in his decreasing exercise tolerance and associated chest pain. This man has worsening stable angina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications for exercise stress testing include: symptoms suggesting myocardial ischaemia, resolved acute chest pain in those without known acute coronary syndrome (ACS), recent ACS treated without coronary angiography and known coronary artery disease (CAD) with worsening symptoms. This man\u0027s history is suggestive of myocardial ischaemia, therefore a stress test was an appropriate next investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn exercise stress test, using the Bruce protocol as in this stem, is used as part of evaluation of a patient with known or suspected coronary disease. The treadmill test, as used in the Bruce protocol, has a sensitivity of ~70% and specificity of ~75% for CAD. Results from the stress test are therefore used in conjunction with a patients clinical history to determine appropriate treatment. This patient demonstrated ST depression in leads II, III and aVF (inferior leads), suggesting partial thickness occlusion of the right coronary artery or the left circumflex artery. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidence of CAD on a stress test, as well as suggestive clinical history, indicate a need for further evaluation and management. This could be to optimise medical therapy, but in this patient, a male, \u0026gt;50 years, with a history of smoking and ST depression evident after four minutes, \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management to assess the severity of CAD. It also has the benefit of allowing stenting in the same procedure if there is significantly coronary artery occlusion identified. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransoesophageal echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful test to identify any valvular or structural dysfunctions of the heart, with greater sensitivity than transthoracic echocardiogram, and should be used in preparation for a CABG. However it is not a first line investigation in the context of angina. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing the stress test\u003C/strong\u003E would not be necessary in this case, and potentially dangerous, given the positive findings at four minutes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery bypass grafting\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated when greater than three vessels are involved. This is currently not known in this patient, and therefore an angiography or CT coronary angiography (CTCA) would need to be performed first. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered if the patient had persistent ST elevation suspected secondary to cardiac ischaemia, and prompt access to percutaneous coronary interventions was not available, however this is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is not a suitable candidate for Calcium scoring as Calcium scoring is not currently recommended for symptomatic patients as per RACGP guidelines\u003Csup\u003E. \u003C/sup\u003EInstead, guidelines recommend the upfront use of stress testing or cardiac CT angiography, which provide assessment of ischaemia and luminal stenosis, respectively. While calcium scoring is a reliable measure of atherosclerotic burden, it does not distinguish between obstructive and non-obstructive CAD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Evidence of coronary artery disease on exercise stress testing demonstrates the need for optimisation of medical management and further investigation with CTCA or angiography.","ST depression in inferior leads during exercise stress testing suggests partial thickness occlusion of the right coronary artery or left circumflex artery.","Angiography is indicated in patients with positive stress tests, especially those with multiple cardiovascular risk factors and typical angina symptoms."],"references":["Vilcant V, Zeltser R. Treatmill Stress Testing. In: Statpearls [online]. 2021; cited 2021 Dec 3].Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499903/","McLellan A, Prior D. Cardiac stress testing - stress electrocardiography and stress echocardiography. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Mar;41(3):119-22. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/march/cardiac-stress-testing","Nicoara A, Skubas N, Ad N, Finley A, Hahn RT, Mahmood F, et al. Guidelines for the Use of Transesophageal Echocardiography to Assist with Surgical Decision-Making in the Operating Room: A Surgery-Based Approach: From the American Society of Echocardiography in Collaboration with the Society of Cardiovascular Anesthesiologists and the Society of Thoracic Surgeons. J Am Soc Echocardiogr. 2020;33(6):692-734. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32503709/","Shahani R. eMedicine: Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting. In: Medscape [Online]. 2019.; cited 2021 December 31. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1893992-overview","Chua A, Blankstein R, Ko B. Coronary artery calcium in primary prevention. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2020;49:464-9. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/august/coronary-artery-calcium-in-primary-prevention"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90596"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"962"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16976"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16976"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c4197927-4083-4b50-bc23-253d9e316808.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c4197927-4083-4b50-bc23-253d9e316808.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":363}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90596"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T08:30:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T18:45:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"962"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108184"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHea